To prove this, we can use the fact that $\nu(G) \leq \nu(G - Y) + |Y|$. This is because removing $Y$ can reduce the matching number by at most $|Y|$.

We also need the fact that $\nu(G - Y) \leq \frac{1}{2}(|V(G) - Y| - \text{odd}(G - Y))$. This is the induction hypothesis from the previous part.

So $\nu(G) \leq \nu(G - Y) + |Y| \leq \frac{1}{2}(|V(G) - Y| - \text{odd}(G - Y)) + |Y| = \frac{1}{2}(|V(G)| + |Y| - \text{odd}(G - Y))$.

Multiplying by 2 gives $2 \nu(G) \leq |V(G)| + |Y| - \text{odd}(G - Y)$, which is what we want.

So the proof strategy is:
1. Show that $\nu(G) \leq \nu(G - Y) + |Y|$
2. Use the induction hypothesis that $\nu(G - Y) \leq \frac{1}{2}(|V(G) - Y| - \text{odd}(G - Y))$
3. Combine these to get the desired inequality

Let's write the Lean proof:

